And again, in another passage :—“ Earth, forsooth, is'far more gloriouS, because, after being wailed over in pestiferous mines of cursed metals by the labour of criminale, it has abandoned the name of earth in fire, and then the fugitive of the mincis changed from torment to ornament, from punishment to delight, from shame to honour.'' ln this passage that most accomplished theologian can be seen to imitate Pliny, who, although a heathen, and indeed an atheist, says in indignation at this luxury: “We penetrate into the bowels of the earth, digging veins of gold and silver, and ores of brass and lead; we seelr also for gems and certain little pebbles Driving galleries into the depths, we draw out the bowels of the earth, that the gems we seek may be worn on the finger.
